ttrs=3D"{&quot;name&quot;:&quot;Richard Hanania&quot;,&quot;id&quot;:631973=
9,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;user&quot;,&quot;url&quot;:null,&quot;photo_url&qu=
ot;:&quot;https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progres=
sive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fim=
ages%2F2de4c8df-7f9c-4bca-901c-53a83a3e97eb_2736x1824.jpeg&quot;,&quot;uuid=
&quot;:&quot;10b784e5-e8c2-4c74-ac37-a1782a399ab9&quot;}" data-component-na=
me=3D"MentionUser">Richard Hanania</a></div><span>, a thought resurfaced in=
 my mind. </span></p><p><span>How much does social media </span><a href=3D"=
https://www.robkhenderson.com/p/the-logic-of-envy" rel=3D"">fuel envy</a><s=
pan>? </span></p><p><span>Young people are actually </span><a href=3D"https=
://www.economist.com/finance-and-economics/2024/04/16/generation-z-is-unpre=
cedentedly-rich" rel=3D"">doing well</a><span>, financially speaking, but m=
any have outsized expectations for themselves.</span></p><p><span>The lifes=
tyles you=E2=80=99re exposed to shape your sense of what=E2=80=99s normal o=
r achievable. When I was a kid, a popular show was MTV </span><em>Cribs</em=
><span>. You=E2=80=99d watch Ludacris show off his mansion in Malibu and th=
ink, =E2=80=9CWow, that=E2=80=99s so cool.=E2=80=9D Sure, there might have =
been a little envy, but Ludacris is a world-renowned hip-hop artist=E2=80=
=94a star=E2=80=94so it made sense that he=E2=80=99d have a mansion like th=
at. You didn=E2=80=99t </span><a href=3D"https://www.robkhenderson.com/p/so=
cial-comparison-orientation-and" rel=3D"">compare yourself</a><span> to him=
 because his success felt like a world away.</span></p><p>But today, it=E2=
=80=99s different. Young people are seeing people who don=E2=80=99t seem al=
l that different from themselves win the social media lottery. Imagine you=
=E2=80=99re 22 or 23, just out of college, and scrolling through Instagram.=
 You see someone your age who looks like you and has a similar level of int=
elligence or talent (maybe the person has no talent at all), but they=E2=80=
=99re making a living as an influencer. They have a few hundred thousand or=
 a million followers and they=E2=80=99re earning money simply by being them=
selves, landing sponsorships and ad deals.</p><p>That kind of exposure can =
activate envy. Young people might think, =E2=80=9CWhy not me? Why can=E2=80=
=99t I have that kind of job?=E2=80=9D It=E2=80=99s one thing to see Ludacr=
is living a glamorous life=E2=80=94that feels understandable and unattainab=
le=E2=80=94but seeing someone so similar to yourself succeeding in a way th=
at looks effortless can feel deeply unfair, especially if you=E2=80=99re st=
ruggling in your own career.</p><p><span>This is because </span><a href=3D"=
https://www.robkhenderson.com/p/evil-eyes-and-tall-poppies" rel=3D"">simila=
rity is one of the strongest predictors</a><span> of whether you envy someo=
ne. The people you envy are those that you could imagine yourself being. Th=
e key components are similarity, and achievement in a domain that is releva=
nt to yourself. So if you want to be an influencer, and you see someone of =
roughly your same age, sex, education level, attractiveness, and so on achi=
eve the ability to earn a living online, you will feel more envy than if it=
 is someone very different from yourself, someone who comes from a complete=
ly different background than you.</span></p><div class=3D"paywall-jump" dat=
a-component-name=3D"PaywallToDOM"></div><p>Here are a few other topics we c=
over:</p><ul><li><p>Chris Rufo=E2=80=99s Job Post Controversy: Richard and =
I speak about a seemingly innocuous tweet about job ads, and why it drew un=
expected backlash from right-leaning accounts</p></li><li><p>Discussing why=
 some view service jobs as "demeaning"</p></li><li><p>As a man, how much do=
es your job status affect your romantic prospects? Richard and I also speak=
 about how immigrants working in service industry jobs navigate different s=
ocial hierarchies from native-born workers</p></li><li><p>Exploring how eco=
nomic concerns, immigration debates, and perceived social hierarchies often=
 intertwine with underlying sexual resentments.</p></li><li><p>How Gen Z's =
inflated financial expectations differ from the modest aspirations of past =
generations</p></li><li><p>Online intellectualism: Exploration of anonymous=
 accounts critiquing societal structures and their aspirations to be part o=
f an intellectual vanguard.</p></li><li><p>The contrast between prestigious=
, high-status careers and the real-world necessity of service industry jobs=
</p></li><li><p>Generational work ethic shift: How modern attitudes toward =
work and fulfillment differ from past generations who saw labor as a means =
to provide for loved ones</p></li><li><p>Richard and I share their own expe=
riences working in restaurants and other service industry jobs</p></li><li>=
<p>The stigma around service jobs and how attitudes towards these roles hav=
e created a need for immigrant labor.</p></li><li><p>My thoughts on seeing =
a 51 year old pizza delivery guy at my doorstep compared with the old days =
when it would be a 19 year old junior college student</p></li><li><p>Declin=
e of religiosity among youth: The dramatic drop in young people's religious=
 participation and its impact on their search for meaning.</p></li></ul><p>=
