v></div><div class=3D"comment-body"><p><span>Is there *good* evidence that =
there is more envy and dissatisfaction today than in the past? All of the s=
uggestions that people today have unrealistic expectations about what their=
 lives should look like seem exactly right, but I wonder to what extent tha=
t has also been true in much of recent history. My suspicion is that dissat=
isfaction and envy are part of the human condition. What causes them and ho=
w people address them change from generation to generation and different in=
dividuals can handle this differently, but they remain.  </span></p><p><spa=
n>It is certainly *possible* that the rate of technological change outpaces=
 the ability of people to adapt emotionally. But human beings are *extremel=
y* good at adjusting to changing conditions in their own live and maintaini=
ng a decent level of happiness independent of external circumstances. </spa=
n></p><p><span>None of this is to we shouldn't consider these issues becaus=
e they will inevitably work out just fine. Ironically, one of the mechanism=
s that leads them to usually work out fine is probably that people think: "=
things are now uniquely bad, we've got to do something about this" and then=
 think of ways to deal with them, both as individuals and by adopting mores=
 and even formal rules. </span></p><p><span>My limited point is that tradit=
ionally many of the solutions have come from bottom up rather than the top =
down. Best to suggest to individuals how to change their perspectives, seco=
nd best is allowing local experiments (like banning the use of phones in sc=
hools). </span></p><div role=3D"button" class=3D"show-all-toggle"><div clas=
