a-hidden-height=3D"224"><p><span>I agree that envy and dissatisfaction have=
 probably been with humans since the beginning of time...but for most of hu=
man history, you'd be comparing yourself to others in your community, which=
 would be a much smaller pool of people to be envious of!  So you might be =
envious of the merchant down the road who was quite prosperous; but you'd a=
lso be aware that you were better off than, say, the beggar in the town squ=
are or the poor widow living in the tumbledown cottage who was trying to ek=
e out a living by doing laundry or whatever.   But you probably weren't com=
paring your life with that of the nobles in the king's court; simply becaus=
e you probably never saw anyone like that.</span></p><p><span>I recall my p=
arents (Silent Generation, both born in 1927) telling me that when they wer=
e growing up during the Depression, they were poor but they didn't realize =
they were poor, because everyone they knew was poor.  </span></p><p><span>B=
oth my parents claimed that people became much more aware of what was lacki=
ng in their material possessions after the advent of TV - both from TV show=
s with families living in big, fancy houses; and also from all the commerci=
als.   While there were commercials on the radio, it wasn't the same as *se=
eing* all the things that could be bought in TV commercials.  Movies certai=
nly  showed people with much more sumptuous lifestyles than most, but I thi=
nk maybe it wasn't as strong an effect - seeing something once in a while o=
n a movie screen isn't quite the same as seeing it every single day in your=
 living room. </span></p><p><span>I was talking with my daughters about som=
ething along these lines - how when I was a teen in the '80s, we girls comp=
ared our looks to the prettiest girl in our school, but nowadays girls are =
comparing themselves to the prettiest girls on the Internet.  Back then, so=
metimes the prettiest girl in school would get a bad haircut, or have a hug=
e zit, or just have a bad day like all humans do;  and you were seeing her =
in real life so you'd know that from a certain angle her nose looked big or=
 whatever.  But the influencers on social media are *only* showing us their=
 best angles, in perfect lighting, with a full face of makeup and all the f=
ilters to make them look inhumanly perfect - and I think that tends to mess=
 with girls' minds.  They start to get the idea that there are people out t=
here who really are that perfect; and even though they probably know *intel=
lectually* that isn't true, I think the sort of subconsciously believe it. =
 </span></p><p><span>So I could see how that would also work with seeing al=
l the people your age who have these high-paying, prestigious, glamorous jo=
bs - you're probably not seeing a lot of content from people who have norma=
l, boring, non-self-actualizing jobs like most of us actually do. </span></=
